                                                                                                                                                                                                     Career highlights
                          Anil kumble: hero of our times                         Anil Kumble (picture from top) appeals for his tenth wicket during the second innings of the India-Pakistan Test at the Kotla in 1999; The leg-spinner bowls with a fractured jaw against the West Indies during the fourth Test at St Johns in 2002; That he can contribute with the bat too was proved when he made his only Test century, against England, at The Oval in August 2007. (Agencies)      
	 Anil Kumble is India rsquo;s leading wicket-taker in both Tests (619) and ODIs (337)         
	 He is Test cricket rsquo;s third highest wicket-taker and seventh highest wicket-taker in ODIs.         
	 He is one of only two bowlers in Test history to have taken all 10 wickets in an innings mdash; the other being Jim Laker of England. He claimed 10/74 against Pakistan at Delhi in February 1999.         
	 Made his Test debut in August 1990 at Old Trafford, Manchester. His first victim was England rsquo;s Allan Lamb.         
	 He took his first 50 Test wickets in just 10 matches, the fastest by an Indian bowler. He is also the fastest to reach 300 and 400 Test wickets for India (66 and 85 matches respectively).         
	 He became the first Indian bowler to claim 500 and 600 Test wickets.         
	 His 156 lbw victims and 35 caught and bowled victims in Tests is the best by any bowler.         
	 He has won four Man of the Series awards.         
	 One of two cricketers (Shane Warne being the other) to take 500 or more wickets and score 2000 runs in Tests.         
	 Got his maiden Test century in his 118th match mdash; the most taken by any batsman to score a Test hundred.         
	 He has taken a total of 956 international wickets.         
	 The third captain from the state of Karnataka after Gundappa Viswanath and Rahul Dravid.         
	 He is the third oldest Indian captain. He first led the side at the age of 37 years and 36 days.         
	 He holds the record for playing most number of Tests before becoming captain. He first led India in his 119th Test.         
	 He is one among seven Indians to win his first Test as captain.           COMPILED BY MOHANDAS MENON                                                                                                                      
